15 veteran owned businesses, especially those that are most in need of increased resources and
16 capacity levels; and
17 WHEREAS, the development of strategies to attract more bidders, and to ensure that such
18 bidders are able to identify bid opportunities, possess the readiness to bid, and are taking
19 advantage of any available state and federal grants and other funding to maximize their
20 viability, may serve to increase the likelihood of participation in state contracts by minority
21 business enterprises, women owned businesses, and veteran owned businesses that are most
22 in need of such opportunities; and
23 WHEREAS, knowing the current level of participation of minority business enterprises,
24 women owned businesses, and veteran owned businesses in state contracts and how this
25 compares to the number of qualified minority business enterprises, women owned
26 businesses, and veteran owned businesses ready, willing, and able to provide goods and
27 services under state contracts is necessary in order to determine what steps and strategies
28 would be most effective in increasing outreach to and improving access for such enterprises
29 and businesses that are most in need.
30 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
31 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
32 on Minority Business Enterprises, Women Owned Businesses, and Veteran Owned
33 Businesses in State Contracting.
34 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of five members of the
35 House of Representatives to be appointed by the Speaker of the House of
36 Representatives. The Speaker shall also appoint an additional three nonlegislative
37 members of the committee, one of whom shall be the owner of a minority business
38 enterprise, one of whom shall be the owner of a women owned business, and one of
